#' Implement this game using a loop over the die rolls.
#'
#' @param num_rolls number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return earned money
#' @export 
#'
#' @examples 
play_dice1 <- function(num_rolls){
  dollor <- 0
  for (i in 1:num_rolls){
    dollor <- dollor -2
    random_number <- sample(1:6, 1)
    if (random_number %% 2 == 0){
      dollor <- dollor + random_number
    }
  }
  return(dollor)
}

play_dice1(3)
[1] -6
play_dice1(3000)
[1] 170
#' Implement this game using built-in R vectorized functions.
#'
#' @param num_rolls number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return earned money
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice2 <- function(num_rolls){
  rolls <- sample(1:6, num_rolls, replace = TRUE)
  even_rolls <- rolls[rolls %% 2 == 0]
  dollors <- num_rolls*(-2) + sum(even_rolls)
  return(dollors)
}
play_dice2(3)
[1] -6
play_dice2(3000)
[1] 136
#' Implement this by collapsing the die rolls into a single table().
#'
#' @param num_rolls number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return earned money
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice3 <- function(num_rolls){
  rolls <- sample(1:6, num_rolls, replace = TRUE)
  roll_counts <- table(rolls)
  roll_counts_df <- as.data.frame(roll_counts)
  roll_counts_df$rolls <- as.numeric(roll_counts_df$rolls)
  dollors <- num_rolls*-2 +  sum((roll_counts_df$rolls[which(roll_counts_df$rolls %% 2 == 0)])*  (roll_counts_df$Freq[which(roll_counts_df$rolls %% 2 == 0)]))
  return(dollors)
  
}
play_dice3(3)
[1] -2
play_dice3(3000)
[1] 20
#' Implement this game by using one of the âapplyâ functions.
#'
#' @param num_rolls number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return earned money
#' 
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice4 <- function(num_rolls){
  rolls <- sample(1:6, num_rolls, replace = TRUE)
  dollors <- num_rolls* -2 + sum(sapply(rolls, function(x) ifelse(x %% 2 == 0, x, 0), simplify = "'array"))
  return(dollors)
}
play_dice4(3)
[1] -4
play_dice4(3000)
[1] 32

part (e)

Yes, itâs a fair game.

To determine whether this dice game is fair or not, we can use a Monte Carlo simulation to simulate the game many times and analyze the outcomes. A fair game is one where the expected value of winnings/losses is zero over many plays.

num_simulations <- 100000

# Simulate the game multiple times
results <- replicate(num_simulations, play_dice2(100))

hist(results)

# Calculate the mean winnings/losses
mean_winnings <- mean(results)

# Print the mean winnings/losses
print(mean_winnings)
[1] -0.00786

The result is quit close to 0, which means you neither win nor lose much money when playing the game, which indicates that the game is fairly balanced.
